A type alias gives an existing type a clearer name. It does not create a new type.

### When to use a type alias

Use a type alias when a type annotation would be repetitive or when a name carries domain meaning.

[codeblock, $code("bst"):
    UserId as Int
    HtmlFragment as String
    RouteParts as {String}
]

### Aliases are transparent

An alias is just another spelling of the same type.

[codeblock, $code("bst"):
    UserId as Int

    id UserId = 42
    raw Int = id
]

`id` has type `UserId`, but it is also an `Int`. You can pass it anywhere an `Int` is expected.

### Alias versus struct

A struct creates a brand new type with its own fields and constructor. An alias does not.

[codeblock, $code("bst"):
    UserId as Int

    User = |
        id Int,
    |
]

`UserId` is `Int`. `User` is a separate type.

### One collection alias

An alias can name a collection type.

[codeblock, $code("bst"):
    Names as {String}

    names Names = {"Ada", "Grace"}
]

### Remember

- A type alias is for naming, not for creating a new type.
- Aliases work in parameters, fields, returns and local annotations.
- Aliases are not values. You cannot pass `UserId` to a function or call it as a constructor. Even when an alias targets a struct or choice, only the target's canonical name constructs.
